### **3. Document Your Language (Clarity)**

Create `THE-HYPERCODE/LANGUAGE_SPEC.md`:

```markdown
# HyperCode Language Specification v0.1

## What is HyperCode?

A neurodivergent-first programming language designed for clarity, accessibility, and multi-paradigm computing (classical, quantum, molecular).

## Basic Syntax

### Missions (Task Definitions)
```hypercode
mission greet {
    set message = "Hello, world!";
    call print(message);
}
```

### Variables
```hypercode
set name = "Lyndz";
set age = 30;
```

### Agent Actions
```hypercode
agent orchestrator do queue("task_name");
```

### Memory Storage
```hypercode
remember note "System initialized";
```

## Grammar (EBNF)

```
program     = statement*
statement   = mission | assignment | call | agent
mission     = "mission" IDENT "{" statement* "}"
assignment  = "set" IDENT "=" value ";"
call        = "call" IDENT ("." IDENT)? "(" args? ")" ";"
agent       = "agent" IDENT "do" IDENT "(" args? ")" ";"
value       = NUMBER | STRING | IDENT
args        = value ("," value)*
```

## Type System (Coming Soon)
Currently untyped. Future versions will support:
- int, float, string, bool
- agent, mission (first-class)
- quantum, molecular types

## Examples

### Hello World
```hypercode
mission hello {
    call print("Hello from HyperCode!");
}
```

### Agent Coordination
```hypercode
mission data_pipeline {
    agent fetcher do load("data.csv");
    agent processor do transform();
    agent saver do store("output.db");
}
```

## Reserved Keywords
mission, agent, set, remember, call, if, for, while, return
```

